            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ajay Patel\u2019s story is woven into the fog and steady rhythm of San Francisco's Outer Sunset. Born in Daly City to Indo-Fijian immigrants, his upbringing was defined by pragmatism and a deep sense of duty. His parents, having fled political instability in Fiji for the promise of the Bay Area, instilled in him a powerful work ethic, teaching him that stability was a greater prize than fleeting passion. School was a means to an end for Ajay; he was a diligent but uninspired student. While classmates talked about college and startups, Ajay was focused on finding a secure path. The day he saw a hiring sign for the United States Postal Service, he saw his future.\n\nAt 19, he started as a mail handler at the massive processing and distribution center in the Bayview. The work was demanding and repetitive, but it was unionized, offered benefits, and promised a pension. For Ajay, it was perfect. Over 25 years, his reliability and meticulous nature saw him rise through the ranks to become a Lead Mail Processor. He is the unseen engine of the city, the man who ensures that birthday cards and ballots, bills and benefit checks all reach their destinations.\n\nHis most significant turning point wasn't professional, but personal. At a community Diwali celebration, he met Sunita, whose family shared a similar Fijian heritage. They married and, for years, saved every spare dollar from his salary. Their proudest achievement was the down payment on a small, two-bedroom row house in the Outer Sunset. This neighborhood, far from the city's frantic core, suited them.\n\nAjay\u2019s life is one of dependable routines. Each morning, he boards the L Taraval Muni for the 7.8-mile journey across town, watching the city wake up. Evenings are for family dinners and helping his teenage daughter, Priya, with her algebra homework. His dreams are not for himself, but for her. He pours his quiet hopes into her future, aspiring to see her attend a university\u2014an opportunity he never had. His personal aspiration is simpler: to one day save enough to take Sunita and Priya to Fiji, to walk the beaches his parents described but he has never seen. He is a man content with his place, finding quiet pride in the vital, steady pulse of his work and the deep love for the family it supports."
